		<post-id xmlns="com-wordpress:feed-additions:1">21242</post-id>	</item>
		<item>
		<title>Oh Sh*t! (When it Hits the Fan, This Kit Helps)</title>
		<link>https://davidduchemin.com/2026/01/oh-sht-when-it-hits-the-fan-this-kit-helps/</link>
					<comments>https://davidduchemin.com/2026/01/oh-sht-when-it-hits-the-fan-this-kit-helps/#comments</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[David]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 18 Jan 2026 14:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[GEAR]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[The Craft]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Travel]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Wilderness]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://davidduchemin.com/?p=21216</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>I was about to photograph a beautiful family of&#160;cheetah in gorgeous morning light when my camera returned an error message and wouldn&#8217;t—no matter what I did—focus. It wouldn&#8217;t even fire. By the time I got my lens swapped onto another body, the action was all over, and I was down a camera at the beginning of a month-long trip. Or ...</p>
The post <a href="https://davidduchemin.com/2026/01/oh-sht-when-it-hits-the-fan-this-kit-helps/">Oh Sh*t! (When it Hits the Fan, This Kit Helps)</a> first appeared on <a href="https://davidduchemin.com">David duChemin - Photographer, Author, Creative Instigator</a>.]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I was about to photograph a beautiful family of&nbsp;cheetah in gorgeous morning light when my camera returned an error message and wouldn&#8217;t—no matter what I did—focus. It wouldn&#8217;t even fire. By the time I got my lens swapped onto another body, the action was all over, and I was down a camera at the beginning of a month-long trip. Or was I?<br><br>Back at camp, I discovered the problem: the flange on the camera, the one to which my lenses mount, was loose and needed a small, very particular screwdriver to fix it. Fortunately, I had one, and I was back up and running. It wasn&#8217;t the first time I&#8217;ve needed something like this to get me out of a jam. A screwdriver or a bit of crazy glue to put my eyeglasses back together. An Arca-Swiss plate for when I&#8217;ve lost one, or—more likely—the bolt I need to attach it. A swab to clean my&nbsp;sensor. Enter the Oh Sh*t Kit.</p>



<p class="has-text-align-center"><em>Prefer to watch a less articulate video version of this short article? You can watch it below. </em><br></p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<div class="x-resp-embed x-is-video x-is-vimeo"><iframe loading="lazy" title="Oh-Shit-Kit" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/1134319094?h=64e89f9817&amp;dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="864" height="486" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"></iframe></div>
</div></figure>



<p><br>A couple of weeks ago, I sent out a quick video about all the stuff you&#8217;d find in my camera bag if you went digging through it and overlooked the obvious gear like cameras and lenses. <a href="https://davidduchemin.com/2025/12/everything-but-the-cameras/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" title="">You can still watch that video or read the article here.</a></p>



<p>Since then, I&#8217;ve been preparing for the coming year, making sure all my gear is where I think it is, and checking that things like the toiletry and pharma kits&nbsp;I take on every trip are stocked with everything&nbsp;I use during a year of travel. And while I was going through it,&nbsp;I thought&nbsp;perhaps there&#8217;s more I could show you, and that it might help those of you who travel to make photographs.</p>



<p>One of the strategies I&#8217;ve found most helpful is thinking in terms of kits. I have a toiletry kit, a pharma kit, a cable kit, a prosthetics kit, and an Oh Sh*t kit. I know what&#8217;s in each, and instead of a packing list that has a bunch of individual items like toothbrush, toothpaste, razor, sunscreen, dental floss, etc., I have one item: toiletry kit. Same with my cable kit. I never have to guess or even double-check that I have my laptop&#8217;s USB-C cable or the one that charges my Apple watch. They&#8217;re all in there, and I <em>only </em>use them for travel. So when &#8220;cable kit&#8221; appears on my packing list, I throw it in the bag and know that it&#8217;s all there.</p>



<p>The only restocking I need to do happens after a trip. I check it all, add more Tylenol or sunblock, replace anything that got lost or broken, and I&#8217;m always ready to go. One of the kits I&#8217;ve had with me the longest, and which has gone through many iterations, is my Oh Sh*t Kit. This used to be a lot more robust, but over the years I&#8217;ve pared it down or split it into other kits. It used to contain a first-aid kit, but now it lives in my camera bag, whereas the Oh Sh*t Kit lives in my duffel, and if I&#8217;m lucky, I won&#8217;t need it at all.</p>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Your kit will reflect your particular needs and will account for&nbsp;how remote your work is. But here&#8217;s what&#8217;s in mine, circa 2026.</strong></h4>



<figure class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-1 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><a href="https://amzn.to/438Ymm8"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1286" height="1286" data-id="21222" src="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby01.png" alt="" class="wp-image-21222" srcset="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby01.png 1286w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby01-150x150.png 150w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby01-500x500.png 500w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby01-768x768.png 768w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby01-100x100.png 100w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby01-864x864.png 864w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby01-1200x1200.png 1200w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1286px) 100vw, 1286px" /></a></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><a href="https://amzn.to/438Ymm8"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1286" height="1286" data-id="21223" src="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby02.png" alt="" class="wp-image-21223" srcset="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby02.png 1286w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby02-150x150.png 150w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby02-500x500.png 500w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby02-768x768.png 768w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby02-100x100.png 100w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby02-864x864.png 864w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Lochby02-1200x1200.png 1200w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1286px) 100vw, 1286px" /></a></figure>
</figure>



<p>My own kit is contained in a <a href="https://amzn.to/438Ymm8" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Lochby Venture Pouch</a> (above) . It&#8217;s not too big, it nestles into my duffle bag anywhere there&#8217;s room, and it&#8217;s got some nice internal organization. You put all this in a ziploc bag if you wanted; it&#8217;s what&#8217;s inside that really matters but I have a number of Lochby products and I really like them.</p>



<p>One side of the pouch contains:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Small microfiber towel, as much for padding as anything else.<br></li>



<li>2 spare insulin pens in case my others break or get stolen by a monkey.<br></li>



<li><a href="https://amzn.to/47mgJ9N" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Gerber Dime multi-tool</a>. This usually goes into the camera bag when I arrive on location so TSA doesn&#8217;t take it from me. This has a bunch of handy little tools, including a little set of pliers and scissors which I use more than the other tools combined.<br></li>



<li><a href="https://amzn.to/4ooeMQa" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Wrench set from Small Rig </a>that has hex wrenches and a couple screwdrivers for things like tripod heads, and in my case, my prosthetic leg.<br></li>



<li><a href="https://amzn.to/4nyFJiN" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">HOTO Precision screwdriver set</a> that comes with 24 different bits, including those really small Phillips, torx and hex bits you need for things like cameras and eyeglasses. I love this little thing and it replaces the handful of tools I once carried.<br></li>



<li><a href="https://www.benchmade.com/products/533" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Benchmade Mini Bug Out</a> pocket knife: super simple, just shy of a 3&#8243; blade, and it weighs only 1.5 ounces or about 43 grams. Like the little multi-tool, I keep this in here until I get where I&#8217;m going. One less thing to remember to pack and one less thing to lose to TSA.<br></li>
</ul>



<figure class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-2 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><a href="https://amzn.to/47mgJ9N"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="800" height="590" data-id="21220" src="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/DIME-800.png" alt="" class="wp-image-21220" srcset="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/DIME-800.png 800w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/DIME-800-150x111.png 150w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/DIME-800-500x369.png 500w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/DIME-800-768x566.png 768w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/DIME-800-100x74.png 100w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><a href="https://amzn.to/4nyFJiN"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="800" height="590" data-id="21218" src="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HOTO-Driver-800.png" alt="" class="wp-image-21218" srcset="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HOTO-Driver-800.png 800w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HOTO-Driver-800-150x111.png 150w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HOTO-Driver-800-500x369.png 500w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HOTO-Driver-800-768x566.png 768w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HOTO-Driver-800-100x74.png 100w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><a href="https://www.benchmade.com/products/533"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="800" height="590" data-id="21221" src="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Benchmade-800.png" alt="" class="wp-image-21221" srcset="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Benchmade-800.png 800w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Benchmade-800-150x111.png 150w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Benchmade-800-500x369.png 500w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Benchmade-800-768x566.png 768w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Benchmade-800-100x74.png 100w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><a href="https://amzn.to/4ooeMQa"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="800" height="590" data-id="21219" src="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/SmallRig-800.png" alt="" class="wp-image-21219" srcset="https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/SmallRig-800.png 800w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/SmallRig-800-150x111.png 150w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/SmallRig-800-500x369.png 500w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/SmallRig-800-768x566.png 768w, https://d3c0aoh0dus5lw.cloudfront.net/WP/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/SmallRig-800-100x74.png 100w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></figure>
</figure>



<p>In the other side of the pouch I have all the little things:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>spare Arca-Swiss plate</li>



<li>spare lens cloth</li>



<li>Zeiss lens wipes</li>



<li>sensor swabs and sensor solution</li>



<li>small vials of Crazy glue</li>



<li>extra business cards</li>



<li>very small bag of extra bolts, screws and bits and pieces for tripods, camera cages, and straps</li>



<li>2 x CR2032 batteries for my remote triggers</li>



<li>pocket-sized duct tape</li>
</ul>



<p>I also used to&nbsp;have a spare pair of eyeglasses in a larger version of this kit, but I keep those in my carry-on now because they do me no good in the cargo hold&nbsp;if I need them while travelling, but I never go far from home without them. I also used to have a small sewing kit, but I&#8217;ve never really had a sewing emergency that would stop me from doing my work, so&nbsp;somewhere along the way, I stopped carrying it.</p>



<p>What about you? Do you bring an emergency kit of any kind when you travel? What&#8217;s in your version of your Oh Sh*t Kit? <a href="https://davidduchemin.com/?p=21216" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">I&#8217;d love to hear about it. Am I missing anything? Feel free to chime in on my blog by clicking here.</a><br><br>For the Love of the Photograph,<br>David</p>



